  <Notes>
    <Note Caller="1" LanguageCode="en" LastEdited="" LastEditedBy="">
      <References>
        <Reference>01911200400026</Reference>
      </References>
      <Content>The subject of this verse is ambiguous: {A:RSV} {A:LXX} "YHWH" | {A:NIV} {A:NJPS} {A:NJB} {A:NRSV} {A:REB} {A:GNT} {A:CEV} "a person" | the former interpretation is to be preferred as terms such as {L:חַנּוּן&lt;SDBH:חַנּוּן&gt;} and {L:רַחוּם&lt;SDBH:רַחוּם&gt;} are attributes of God alone.</Content>
    </Note>
    <Note Caller="2" LanguageCode="en" LastEdited="" LastEditedBy="">
      <References>
        <Reference>02304902400018</Reference>
      </References>
      <Content>{A:MT} {A:NJPS} "victor" | {A:HOTTP}-C {A:RSV} {A:NIV} {A:NJB} {A:NRSV} {A:REB} {A:GNT} {A:CEV} {L:עָרִיץ&lt;SDBH:עָרִיץ&gt;}</Content>
    </Note>
    <Note Caller="3" LanguageCode="en" LastEdited="" LastEditedBy="">
      <References>
        <Reference>03800900900024</Reference>
      </References>
      <Content>This passage is rendered differently in various translations. {A:RSV}, {A:NRSV}, {A:NJPS} suggest "triumphant," {A:NJB} has "vindicated," {A:REB} has "his cause won." These all relate to an aspect of meaning, "victorious." Other versions ({A:KJV}, {A:NIV}, NAB etc.) prefer the traditional "just."</Content>
    </Note>
  </Notes>
